# ESP-P4 Peripheral Binding and DMA Safety

## Critical Rule: Never Assign DMA-Driven Peripherals to GPIOs Outside Their Native I/O Group

**Problem**: On the ESP32-P4, some GPIOs are not connected to the high-speed I/O matrix (HP IOMUX).  
Using non-native pins for SPI, SDIO, I²S, or LCD DMA will cause bus contention, performance penalties, or outright driver failures.

**Solution**: Always select GPIOs directly bonded to the target peripheral’s I/O group and avoid GPIO matrix rerouting for high-speed devices.

### ✅ CORRECT (Native SPI2 DMA Capable Pins)
```c
// SPI2 (Display or LED controller)
#define PIN_SPI2_MOSI   11
#define PIN_SPI2_MISO   13
#define PIN_SPI2_SCK    12
#define PIN_SPI2_CS     10
spi_bus_config_t buscfg = {
    .mosi_io_num = PIN_SPI2_MOSI,
    .miso_io_num = PIN_SPI2_MISO,
    .sclk_io_num = PIN_SPI2_SCK,
    .max_transfer_sz = 4096,
    .flags = SPICOMMON_BUSFLAG_MASTER | SPICOMMON_BUSFLAG_DMA,
};
```

### WRONG (GPIOs Outside HP I/O Group)
```c
// SPI2 on GPIO40–43 (non-native for HP domain)
spi_bus_initialize(SPI2_HOST, &buscfg, SPI_DMA_CH_AUTO); // May fail at 20–40 MHz

```

### Key Principles

1. Use native high-speed GPIOs for SPI, I²S, and SDIO; avoid remapped or LP (low-power) domains.
2. Enable DMA descriptors in IRAM (or SRAM1) to avoid PSRAM cache invalidation issues.
3. Disable flash cache only during DMA critical sections if required.
4. Always prefer spi_bus_initialize() with SPICOMMON_BUSFLAG_DMA.

### Available P4 Pins on ESP32-P4-WIFI6 board:

GPIO2-GPIO5, GPIO7, GPIO8, GPIO20-GPIO33, GPIO46-GPIO52
Used pins are declared in /firmware/shared/config/pin_config.h
